        <example>
            <p>Let <m>x</m> represent the price of a new <m>60</m>-inch television at Target on Black Friday (which was <m>\$650</m>), and let <m>y</m> be the number of hours you will watch something on this TV over its lifetime. What is the relationship between <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>?</p>

            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                <p>Well, there is no getting around the fact that <m>x=650</m>. As for <m>y</m>, without any extra information about your viewing habits, it could theoretically be as low as <m>0</m> or it could be anything larger than that. If we graph this scenario, we have to graph the equation <m>x=650</m> which we now know to give a vertical line, and we get <xref ref="figure-television">Figure</xref>. </p>
                <figure xml:id="figure-television">
                    <caption>New TV: hours watched versus purchase price; negative <m>y</m>-values omitted since they make no sense in context</caption>
                    <image>
                        <description>the vertical line x=650, starting at the point (650,0) with an arrow pointing upward</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-100,xmax=1000,
                                        ymin=-100,ymax=1000,
                                        xtick={200,400,...,800},
                                        minor xtick={100,300,...,900},
                                        ytick={200,400,...,800},
                                        minor ytick={100,300,...,900},
                                        ylabel={hours watched},
                                        xlabel={purchase price},
                                        ]
                                \addplot+[->] coordinates {(650,0) (650,1000)};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(650,0)};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
        </example>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Summary of Horizontal and Vertical Line Equations</title>
            <statement>
                <sidebyside>
                    <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                        <col width="50%" right="medium"/>
                        <col width="50%" />
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Horizontal Lines</cell>
                            <cell>Vertical Lines</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><p>A line is <term>horizontal</term> if and only if its equation can be written <me>y=k</me> for some constant <m>k</m>.</p></cell>
                            <cell><p>A line is <term>vertical</term> if and only if its equation can be written <me>x=h</me> for some constant <m>h</m>.</p></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><p>In <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref>, any line with equation <me>0x+By=C</me> is horizontal.</p></cell>
                            <cell><p>In <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref>, any line with equation <me>Ax+0y=C</me> is vertical.</p></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><p>If the line with equation <m>y=k</m> is horizontal, it has a <m>y</m>-intercept at <m>(0,k)</m> and has slope <m>0</m>.</p></cell>
                            <cell><p>If the line with equation <m>x=h</m> is vertical, it has an <m>x</m>-intercept at <m>(h,0)</m> and its slope is <em>undefined</em>. Some say it has <em>no</em> slope, and some say the slope is <em>infinitely large</em>.</p></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="none">
                            <cell><p>In <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="title">slope-intercept form</xref>, any line with equation <me>y=0x+b</me> is horizontal.</p></cell>
                            <cell><p>It's impossible to write the equation of a vertical line in <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="title">slope-intercept form</xref>, because vertical lines do not have a defined slope.</p></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
        </paragraphs>

    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsection-parallel-lines">
        <title>Parallel Lines</title>

        <example>
            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                <p>Two trees were planted in the same year, and their growth over time is modeled by the two lines in <xref ref="figure-trees">Figure</xref>. Use linear equations to model each tree's growth, and interpret their meanings in this context.</p>

                <figure xml:id="figure-trees">
                    <caption>Two Trees' Growth Chart</caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                    <description>This is a Cartesian grid with two parallel lines. Tree 1 has a slope triangle from (0,2) to (3,4) for a slope of 2/3. Tree 2 has a slope triangle from (0,5) to (3.7) for a slope of 2/3.</description>
                    <latex-image>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                xlabel={$x$ time in years},ylabel={$y$ height in feet},
                                xmin=-1,xmax=5,ymin=-1,ymax=9,
                                minor ytick=,
                                xtick={-1,0,...,4},ytick={-1,0,...,8}]

                                \addplot+[domain = 0:5,->]{2/3*x+2} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above] {Tree 1};
                                \addplot+[domain = 0:5,->]{2/3*x+5} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above] {Tree 2};

                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,2)} node[below right] {$(0,2)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,4)} node[below right] {$(3,4)$};
                                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,2) (3,2)} node[pos=0.5] {$3$};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,2) (3,3.7)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$2$};

                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[below right] {$(0,5)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,7)} node[below right] {$(3,7)$};
                                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,5) (3,5)} node[pos=0.5] {$3$};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,5) (3,6.7)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$2$};
                            \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

            <p>We can see Tree 1's equation is <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+2\text{,}</m> and Tree 2's equation is <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+5\text{.}</m> Tree 1 was <m>2</m> feet tall when it was planted, and Tree 2 was <m>5</m> feet tall when it was planted. Both trees have been growing at the same rate, <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> feet per year, or <m>2</m> feet every <m>3</m> years.</p>

            <p>An important observation right now is that those two lines are parallel. Why? For lines with positive slopes, the bigger a line's slope, the steeper the line is slanted. As a result, if two lines have the same slope, they are slanted at the same angle, thus they are parallel.</p>

        </example>

        <fact xml:id="fact-parallel-lines"><idx><h>parallel lines</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>Any two vertical lines are parallel to each other. For two non-vertical lines, they are parallel if and only if they have the same slope.</p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                        parser::Assignment->Allow;
                        $line=Formula("y=17.2x+128.2");
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>A line <m>\ell</m> is parallel to the line with equation <m>y=17.2x-340.9</m>, but <m>\ell</m> has <m>y</m>-intercept at <m>(0,128.2)</m>. What is an equation for <m>\ell</m>?</p>
                    <p><var name="$line" width="20" /></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Parallel lines have the same slope, and the slope of <m>y=17.2x-340.9</m> is <m>17.2</m>. So <m>\ell</m> has slope <m>17.2</m>. And we have been given that <m>\ell</m>'s <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,128.2)</m>. So we can use slope-intercept form to write its equation as <me>y=17.2x+128.2\text{.}</me></p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                        parser::Assignment->Allow;
                        $line=Formula("y=-3.5(x+12)+23");
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>A line <m>\kappa</m> is parallel to the line with equation <m>y=-3.5x+17</m>, but <m>\kappa</m> passes through the point <m>(-12,23)</m>. What is an equation for <m>\kappa</m>?</p>
                    <p><var name="$line" width="20" /></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Parallel lines have the same slope, and the slope of <m>y=-3.5x+17</m> is <m>-3.5</m>. So <m>\kappa</m> has slope <m>-3.5</m>. And we know a point that <m>\kappa</m> passes through, so we can use point-slope form to write its equation as <me>y=-3.5(x+12)+23\text{.}</me></p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>


    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>Perpendicular Lines</title>

        <p>The slopes of two perpendicular lines have a special relationship too.</p>

        <p><xref ref="figure-perpendicular-lines">Figure</xref> walks you through an explanation of this realationship.</p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-perpendicular-lines">
            <caption>The relationship between slopes of perpendicular lines</caption>
            <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%" margins="0%">
            <figure>
                <caption>Two generic perpendicular lines, where one has slope <m>m</m>.</caption>
                <image>
                <description>the graph of two perpendicular lines, where one has a slope of m</description>
                <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-2,
                                ymin=-2,
                                ticks=none,
                                grid=none,
                                axis equal,
                                ]
                        \addplot+[domain=-2:7]{0.5*x+2.5} node[pos=0.7,sloped,above] {slope $m$};
                        \addplot+[domain=-1:3.5]{-2*x+5};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <figure>
                <caption>Since the one slope is <m>m</m>, we can draw a slope triangle with <q>run</q> <m>1</m> and <q>rise</q> <m>m</m>.</caption>
                <image>
                <description>the previous graph with a slope triangle added; the rise is m and the run is 1</description>
                <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-2,
                                ymin=-2,
                                ticks=none,
                                grid=none,
                                axis equal,
                                ]
                        \addplot+[domain=-2:7]{0.5*x+2.5};
                        \addplot+[domain=-1:3.5]{-2*x+5};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,3) (5,3)} node[above,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(5,3) (5,5)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$m$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <figure>
                <caption>A <em>congruent</em> slope triangle can be drawn for the perpendicular line. It's legs have the same lengths, but in different positions, and one is negative.</caption>
                <image>
                <description>the previous graph with the perpendicular line and its slope triangle added; the perpendicular line has a rise of -1 and a run of m which gives a slope of -1/m</description>
                <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-2,
                                ymin=-2,
                                ticks=none,
                                grid=none,
                                axis equal,
                                ]
                        \addplot+[domain=-2:7]{0.5*x+2.5};
                        \addplot+[domain=-1:3.5]{-2*x+5};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,3) (5,3)};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(5,3) (5,5)};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,3) (3,3)} node[below,pos=0.5] {$m$};
                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,3) (3,-1)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$-1$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            </sidebyside>
        </figure>

        <p>The second line in <xref ref="figure-perpendicular-lines">Figure</xref> has slope <me>\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{-1}{m}=-\frac{1}{m}\text{.}</me></p>

        <fact xml:id="fact-perpendicular-lines"><idx><h>perpendicular lines</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>A vertical line and a horizontal line are perpendicular. For lines that are neither vertical nor horizontal, they are perpendicular if and only if the slope of one is the negative reciprocal of the slope of the other. That is, if one has slope <m>m</m>, the other has slope <m>-\frac{1}{m}</m>.</p>

                <p>Another way to say this is that the product of the slopes of two perpendicular lines is <m>-1</m> (assuming both of the lines have a slope in the first place).</p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <p>Not convinced? Here are three pairs of perpendicular lines where we can see if the pattern holds.</p>

        <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%" margins="0%">
            <figure>
                <caption>Graphing <m>y=2x-2</m> and <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+2</m>. Note the relationship between their slopes: <m>2=-\frac{1}{-\sfrac{1}{2}}</m></caption>
                <image>
                <description>the graph of lines y=2x-2 and y=-1/2x+2 showing that they are perpendicular lines.</description>
                <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[axis equal]
                            \addplot+[domain = -2.5:4.5]{2*x-2} node[pos=0.15,sloped,above]{$y=2x-2$};
                            \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{-0.5*x+2} node[pos=0.15,sloped,above]{$y=-\frac{1}{2}x+2$};
                        \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <figure>
                <caption>Graphing <m>y=-3x+4</m> and <m>y=\frac{1}{3}x-3</m>. Note the relationship between their slopes: <m>-3=-\frac{1}{\sfrac{1}{3}}</m></caption>
                <image>
                <description>the graph of lines y=-3x+4 and y=1/3x-3 showing that they are perpendicular.</description>
                <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[axis equal]
                            \addplot+[domain = -1:3.666]{-3*x+4} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above]{$y=-3x+4$};
                            \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{1/3*x-3} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above]{$y=\frac{1}{3}x-3$};
                        \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <figure>
                <caption>Graphing <m>y=x</m> and <m>y=-x</m>. Note the relationship between their slopes: <m>1=-\frac{1}{-1}</m></caption>
                <image>
                <description>the graph of lines y=x and y=-x showing that they are perpendicular</description>
                <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[axis equal]
                            \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{x} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above]{$y=x$};
                            \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{-x} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above]{$y=-x$};
                        \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>


        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Line <m>A</m> passes through <m>(-2,10)</m> and <m>(3,-10)\text{.}</m> Line <m>B</m> passes through <m>(-4,-4)</m> and <m>(8,-1)\text{.}</m> Determine whether these two lines are parallel, perpendicular or neither.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will use the slope formula to find both lines' slopes:<md>
                    <mrow>\text{Line }A\text{'s slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\amp\text{Line }B\text{'s slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10-10}{3-(-2)}\amp\amp=\frac{-1-(-4)}{8-(-4)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-20}{5}\amp\amp=\frac{3}{12}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-4\amp\amp=\frac{1}{4}</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>Their slopes are not the same, so those two lines are not parallel.</p>

                <p>The product of their slopes is <m>(-4)\cdot\frac{1}{4}=-1\text{,}</m> which means the two lines are perpendicular.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
                        parser::Assignment->Allow;
                        $line=Formula("y=3/2(x-4)-3");
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>Line <m>A</m> and Line <m>B</m> are perpendicular. Line <m>A</m>'s equation is <m>2x+3y=12\text{.}</m> Line <m>B</m> passes through the point <m>(4,-3)\text{.}</m> Find an equation for Line <m>B</m>.</p>
                    <p><var name="$line" width="20" /></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>First, we will find Line <m>A</m>'s slope by rewriting its equation from standard form to slope-intercept form:<md>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\amp=12</mrow>
                        <mrow>3y\amp=12\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
                        <mrow>3y\amp=-2x+12</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{-2x+12}{3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+4</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                    <p>So Line <m>A</m>'s slope is <m>-\frac{2}{3}\text{.}</m> Since Line <m>B</m> is perpendicular to Line <m>A</m>, its slope is <m>-\frac{1}{-\frac{2}{3}}=\frac{3}{2}</m>.</p>

                    <p>It's also given that Line <m>B</m> passes through <m>(4,-3)\text{,}</m> so we can write Line <m>B</m>'s point-slope form equation:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_0)+y_0</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=\frac{3}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
                    </md></p>

                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>
