            <title>Challenge</title>

            <exercise><!-- Kara's challenge problem -->
                <webwork>
                    <statement>
                        <p>Prove that a triangle with vertices at the points <m>(1, 1)</m>, <m>(-4, 4)</m>, and <m>(-3, 0)</m> is a right triangle.</p>
                        <p><var form="essay"/></p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>The slope between <m>(1,1)</m> and <m>(-3,0)</m> is <m> \frac{0-1}{-3 - (-1)}</m> or <m> \frac{1}{4} </m>.</p>
                        <p>The slope between <m>(-3,0)</m> and <m>(-4,4)</m> is <m> \frac{4-0}{-4 - (-3)}</m> or <m> \frac{-4}{1} </m>.</p>
                        <p>Since <m> \frac{1}{4} </m> and <m> \frac{-4}{1} </m> are negative reciprocals, those two sides are perpendicular.  Thus, the triangle is a right triangle.</p>
                    </solution>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>
